Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Slovakia.
Entry and borders
Slovakia has closed its international airports at Bratislava, Kosice and Poprad to scheduled passenger flights. Those returning to Slovakia from abroad will be instructed to self-isolate at home for 14 days.
As of 13 March, entry to Slovakia is permitted only for Slovak citizens and foreign residents. British nationals with proof of temporary or permanent residence are allowed to enter the country by land border. All those arriving from abroad are required to self-isolate for 14 days.
For information on how to return to the UK from Slovakia, see Return to the UK
Local measures
On 12 March, the Slovak government declared a State of Emergency and announced a range of restrictions on travel and events. No end date has been specified for most of these.
All public gatherings have been banned, including sporting events and religious services. This includes theatres and cinemas, but not workplaces, supermarkets and pharmacies. All schools and universities are closed until further notice.
Local public transport is running on a reduced timetable. You must wear a mask or otherwise cover your nose and mouth when travelling.
Restrictions apply to all public, social, sporting and cultural activity. All tourist and leisure sites, including ski resorts, spas and museums are closed. Many restaurants and hotels and all bars and nightclubs are closed. Most shops are also closed with exceptions for the sale of food, banks, pharmacies and petrol stations. Face masks are mandatory anywhere outside the home.
Further information
Further advice and information is available on the Slovak government website.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Slovakia on the TravelHealthPro country page.
